<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="587" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,367,392]" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis box="[921,1000,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">cinctus</emphasis>
”, referring to the aedeagus with a pair of apical processes curved ventrobasally (
<figureCitation box="[618,719,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1690,1713]" captionTargetBox="[165,1417,193,1648]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[162,1424,193,1669]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Arboridia cincta Song &amp; Li, sp. nov.: 1, Abdominal apodemes; 2, Pygofer lobe, lateral view; 3, Subgenital plate; 4, Style; 5, Aedeagus, lateral view; 6, Aedeagus, ventral view; 7, Connective." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238916/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="587">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
